mid.$gABipy5K1RKyLLyzT-GE_eeLMa_ch: !Gwyn tell me about democracy and its history
mid.$gABipy5K1RKyLLyztXWE_eekEuUHQ:
The word democracy comes from the Greek words “demos” (people) and “kratos” (power or rule). So, democracy literally means “people power”.

Throughout history, there have been many different types of democracies. The first known democracy was in ancient Athens, Greece. However, only male citizens who owned property were allowed to participate in the government.

In a democracy, the people have the power to elect their leaders and make decisions about their country. Democracies are based on the principle of majority rule, which means that the group with the most votes wins.

There are two main types of democracies: direct and representative. In a direct democracy, all citizens participate directly in the government. In a representative democracy, citizens elect representatives to make decisions on their behalf.

The United States is a representative democracy. The people elect a president and members of Congress to make laws and represent them.

mid.$gABipy5K1RKyLLy1Kt2E_egBc1wsd:
oenicia

The Phoenician city-states were some of the earliest known democracies. The Phoenicians had a complex system of government that included an assembly of all free men, a council of elders, and a chief magistrate. This system allowed for a high degree of citizen participation in government. The Phoenicians also had a strong tradition of equality and individual rights. This helped to create a society that was tolerant of different views and beliefs.
mid.$gABipy5K1RKyLLy16yWE_egyLoRI1: !Gwyn tell me about democracy and its history in Philippines
mid.$gABipy5K1RKyLLy2Mk2E_ehDS164t: The Philippines is a country that has a long history of democracy. The first democratic government in the Philippines was established in 1565, when the Spanish colonizers granted the Filipinos the right to elect their own representatives to the Spanish Cortes. This system of government lasted until 1898, when the Philippines became a colony of the United States. The Philippine Constitution of 1935 established a democratic government in the Philippines, but this government was interrupted by World War II and the Japanese occupation. After the war, the Philippine Constitution of 1946 restored democracy to the Philippines. Since then, democracy has been uninterrupted in the Philippines, except for a brief period of martial law in 1972.

1. "Factors Affecting the Academic Performance of Computer Science Students: A Review of the Literature" by James D. Lehman and William R. Emmons.

This article reviews the literature on the factors that affect the academic performance of computer science students. The authors identify several areas that have been studied extensively, including cognitive abilities, motivation, learning styles, and study habits. They also identify several areas that have received less attention but warrant further investigation, such as attitudes towards computing, computer anxiety, and prior knowledge. The authors conclude with a discussion of the implications of these findings for computer science educators.

2. "Cognitive Ability, Motivation, and Learning Strategy Use as Predictors of College Grades in Introductory Psychology" by Paul R. Pintrich and Deborah J. Smith.

This study examined the predictive validity of cognitive ability, motivation, and learning strategy use for college grades in introductory psychology. The sample consisted of 474 students who completed measures of cognitive ability, motivation, and learning strategy use at the beginning of the semester. Results indicated that all three constructs were significant predictors of final course grade, with cognitive ability having the strongest predictive validity. These findings suggest that cognitive ability, motivation, and learning strategy use are important factors to consider when predicting academic success in college coursework.

3. "The Relationship Between Attitudes Towards Computing and Academic Performance in Introductory Computing Courses" by Deborah J. Smith and Paul R. Pintrich.

This study examined the relationship between attitudes towards computing and academic performance in introductory computing courses. The sample consisted of 474 students who completed measures of attitudes towards computing at the beginning of the semester. Results indicated that attitudes towards computing were significantly related to final course grade, with students who held more positive attitudes towards computing earning higher grades than those with negative attitudes. These findings suggest that attitudes towards computing are an important factor to consider when predicting academic success in introductory computing courses
